Test that `dune describe workspace` reports the origin of each module: a
plain source file, a file generated by a `rule` stanza, one generated by
`ocamllex`, one generated by `ocamlyacc`, and the alias module synthesised by
dune itself when wrapping. Exercised for a wrapped library, an unwrapped
library, and an executable.

The dependencies of a `rule`-generated module are opt-in, via
`--with-origin-deps` and `--with-origin-deps-expanded` (see the end of the
test).

  $ cat >dune-project <<EOF
  > (lang dune 3.20)
  > EOF

A wrapped library with all four kinds of source, plus its alias module.

  $ cat >dune <<EOF
  > (library
  >  (name mylib))
  > (ocamllex lexer)
  > (ocamlyacc gram)
  > (rule
  >  (target generated.ml)
  >  (deps (glob_files *.txt))
  >  (action (write-file generated.ml "let x = 0")))
  > EOF

  $ cat >plain.ml <<EOF
  > let x = 0
  > EOF

  $ touch dep.txt extra.txt

  $ cat >lexer.mll <<EOF
  > rule read = parse
  > | eof { () }
  > EOF

  $ cat >gram.mly <<EOF
  > %token EOF
  > %start main
  > %type <unit> main
  > %%
  > main: EOF { () }
  > EOF

A library declared under `(subdir ...)`: the generated origins must point at the
dune file the stanza is actually written in (the parent `dune`), not at the
non-existent `sub/dune`.

  $ mkdir -p sub
  $ cat >>dune <<EOF
  > (subdir sub
  >  (library
  >   (name sublib)))
  > EOF

  $ cat >sub/s.ml <<EOF
  > let x = 0
  > EOF

An unwrapped library: no alias module is synthesised.

  $ mkdir -p unwrapped
  $ cat >unwrapped/dune <<EOF
  > (library
  >  (name mylib_unwrapped)
  >  (wrapped false))
  > (ocamllex ulexer)
  > EOF

  $ cat >unwrapped/u.ml <<EOF
  > let x = 0
  > EOF

  $ cat >unwrapped/ulexer.mll <<EOF
  > rule read = parse
  > | eof { () }
  > EOF

An executable, exercising the separate executables code path.

  $ mkdir -p exe
  $ cat >exe/dune <<EOF
  > (executable
  >  (name main))
  > (ocamllex elexer)
  > (rule
  >  (target egen.ml)
  >  (action (write-file egen.ml "let x = 0")))
  > EOF

  $ cat >exe/main.ml <<EOF
  > let () = ignore Elexer.read; ignore Egen.x
  > EOF

  $ cat >exe/elexer.mll <<EOF
  > rule read = parse
  > | eof { () }
  > EOF

